AWS Elastic Load Balancing (ELB) automatically distributes incoming application traffic across multiple targets—such as EC2 instances, containers, and IP addresses—across multiple Availability Zones. 

It increases application fault tolerance, provides high availability, and automatically scales to handle traffic changes. 

ELB serves as a single point of contact for clients, monitoring target health and routing traffic only to healthy instances. 

Application Load Balancer (ALB): Best for HTTP/HTTPS traffic, operating at Layer 7 to route requests based on content (path-based, host-based routing).

Network Load Balancer (NLB): Ideal for high-performance TCP/UDP traffic, operating at Layer 4 and capable of handling millions of requests per second with low latency.

Gateway Load Balancer (GWLB): Used to deploy and manage third-party virtual appliances (firewalls, inspection tools).

Classic Load Balancer (CLB): Legacy load balancer for basic EC2-Classic

High Availability: Distributes traffic across multiple Availability Zones (AZs) to ensure uninterrupted service if one instance or AZ fails.

Health Checks: Continuously monitors backend targets and stops sending traffic to unhealthy ones.

Security: Supports SSL/TLS termination, allowing you to manage certificates via AWS Certificate Manager (ACM).

Scalability: Automatically adjusts capacity based on traffic fluctuations without manual intervention.

Integration: Integrates with Amazon ECS for container balancing, Auto Scaling, and AWS WAF for security. 

